Graph:-
A Graph is a non-linear data structure used to represent relationships between objects.
It consists of vertices (nodes) and edges (connections).
Graphs can be directed or undirected, weighted or unweighted.
They are commonly used to model real-world systems such as social networks, maps, flight routes, and computer networks.
Graphs are typically stored using adjacency lists or adjacency matrices.
BFS and DFS are the two most common algorithms used to traverse graphs.
The time complexity of graph traversal is O(V + E), where V is the number of vertices and E is the number of edges.

Types of Graphs
1. Undirected Graph
 Connection works both ways.
 A ----- B
 Means:
 A ↔ B

 Example:
 Facebook friendship
 WhatsApp contacts

2. Directed Graph (Digraph)
Connection has direction.
A → B
Means:
A can reach B
B cannot necessarily reach A
Example:
Instagram follow
Twitter follow

3. Weighted Graph
Edges have weights/costs.
A --5-- B
 \      |
 2      3
  \     |
    C

Example:
Google Maps
Flight routes

Weight can represent:
Distance
Cost
Time

4.Unweighted Graph
An Unweighted Graph looks similar, but there are no weights (numbers) on the edges.
A ----- B
 \     /
  \   /
    C
    or
    A ----- B
    |
    |
    C

->Example:
Facebook friendships
LinkedIn connections
Computer network connections
Social networks
->Edge Represents:
Friendship
Connection
Relationship
Communication link

=>How Graph is Stored?
-> Adjacency List (Most Common)
  Graph:
  A ---- B
  |
  |
  C

  Stored as:
  A -> [B, C]
  B -> [A]
  C -> [A]
->Adjacency DSA.Matrix
  Graph:
  A ---- B
  |
  |
  C
  Stored as:
       A B C
  A    0 1 1
  B    1 0 0
  C    1 0 0

  1 = Connected
  0 = Not Connected

=>Graph Traversal
 Two important algorithms:
 ->BFS (Breadth First Search)
 Uses Queue.
 Visits level by level.

 ->DFS (Depth First Search)
   Uses Stack or Recursion.
   Goes deep first.

 Example Graph
        A
       / \
      B   C
     / \
    D   E

  BFS
  A → B → C → D → E

  DFS
  A → B → D → E → C

=>Java Representation
  Using Adjacency List:
  import java.util.*;

  public class GraphExample {

      public static void main(String[] args) {

          Map<String, List<String>> graph = new HashMap<>();

          graph.put("A", Arrays.asList("B", "C"));
          graph.put("B", Arrays.asList("D", "E"));
          graph.put("C", Arrays.asList());
          graph.put("D", Arrays.asList());
          graph.put("E", Arrays.asList());

          System.out.println(graph);
      }
  }

  O/P:-
  {
  A=[B, C],
  B=[D, E],
  C=[],
  D=[],
  E=[]
  }

=>Time Complexity
  Using Adjacency List:
  BFS
  O(V + E)
  DFS
  O(V + E)

  Where:
  V = Vertices (Nodes)
  E = Edges (Connections)

